We have shown for the first time, that naturally occurring magnetic particles which are inhomogeneously magnetised are more reliable recorders of the ancient geomagnetic field than the previously regarded 'ideal' particles of uniform single -domain states. This is a significant finding because virtually all palaeomagnetic recordings are made in inhomgenously magnetic grains.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>By palaeomagnetists and geologists attempting to estimate the fidelity of magnetic recordings in rock samples. Thereby obtaining a better understanding of the variation of the past geomagnetic field and the motion of the continents. 

